Issues.Body:
Ok, I want to compile a string which is a c# script/code in my app.
I did what https://github.com/dotnet/wpf/issues/8880 says so now AutomationElement/AutomationEvent is accessible.
But the issue is... how to use UIAutomationClient and/or UIAutomationTypes as references for CSharpCompilation.Create()
I looked at the code in https://github.com/jaredpar/basic-reference-assemblies and tried this but failed with error:

      var assembly = typeof(AutomationElement).GetTypeInfo().Assembly;
      var names = assembly.GetManifestResourceNames(); // this is to get the name to be used in the next line, so you can ignore.
      var stream = assembly.GetManifestResourceStream("FxResources.UIAutomationClient.SR.resources");
      var bytes = new byte[stream.Length];
      using var memoryStream = new MemoryStream(bytes);
      stream.CopyTo(memoryStream);
      var iArray = ImmutableCollectionsMarshal.AsImmutableArray(bytes);
      var ref = AssemblyMetadata.CreateFromImage(iArray).GetReference()
     CSharpCompilation.Create(..., ..., new[] {ref}, ...);
     using (var dllStream = new MemoryStream())
     {
        var emitResult = cSharpCompilation.Emit(dllStream);

Here, emiResult says 

error CS0009: Metadata file '<in-memory assembly>' could not be opened -- PE image doesn't contain managed metadata. | Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.Diagnostic {Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.CSharp.CSDiagnostic}

So, in short, I have byte array, then how could I use that as a reference for CSharpCompilation.Create()
Maybe the issue is that the resource is NOT a managed code... then how to use it for CSharpCompilation.Create()?
Thanks!

_This issue has been moved from [a ticket on Developer Community](https://developercommunity.visualstudio.com/t/multiple-crashes-generating-a-response/10944275)._

